<subSubSection id="E8715928B24E69E7430674FB4A943720" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="B1D80877EE35E25FBEB35B5AE489EE60" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0673BB75F2D6A838CCA7E58F1687454C" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
The phylogenetic analysis supports (with high values of bootstrap and Bayesian posterior probabilities 100/1) the distinction of 
<taxonomicName id="0CD1E675A8C0A948AD819DC42AA59BF7" authorityName="M. Herrera, Bandala &amp; Montoya" authorityYear="2021" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Cantharellaceae" genus="Cantharellus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cantharellus parvoflavus" order="Cantharellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="parvoflavus">
<emphasis id="8E7C1B023201AE43FDCD0EF3C283ABF3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Cantharellus parvoflavus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a new species, sister to 
<taxonomicName id="2FEA79E0DC58E4C64C848130EC0F63A3" genus="C." lsidName="C. appalachiensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="appalachiensis">
<emphasis id="884323DC89E16FB43C629D5AA7655E31" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. appalachiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from USA. This latter species, besides their basidiomes being somewhat larger [pileus 10-50 mm/stipe 15-75 
<normalizedToken id="4D72684E566884D412B778306DDD959C" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-10 (-13) mm], are not distinctly yellow, only dingy yellow, usually dull brown, pale or yellowish-brown at margin, darker to brown on disc (
<bibRefCitation id="6537866C04AB615EEFAECD42ABB2631D" author="Petersen, RH" journalOrPublisher="Economic Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" refId="B45" refString="Petersen, RH, Ryvarden, L, 1971. Notes on cantharelloid fungi IV. Two new species of Cantharellus. Svensk Bot. Tidskr.65: 399-405." title="Notes on cantharelloid fungi IV. Two new species of Cantharellus. Svensk Bot. Tidskr. 65: 399 - 405." year="1971">Petersen and Ryvarden 1971</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="523F92793EA7631A301C64E26AEA92B6" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1978.12020280" author="Bigelow, HE" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="707 - 756" refId="B5" refString="Bigelow, HE, 1978. The cantharelloid fungi of New England and adjacent areas. Mycologia 70 (4): 707 - 756, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1978.12020280" title="The cantharelloid fungi of New England and adjacent areas." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1978.12020280" volume="70" year="1978">Bigelow 1978</bibRefCitation>
). Moreover, 
<taxonomicName id="ED6EE7619DB4FBB0D01DC6815C0D5859" genus="C." lsidName="C. appalachiensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="appalachiensis">
<emphasis id="2B4EA2D558953EB9BFEFADAB9E85A2C6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. appalachiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has wider broadly-ellipsoid basidiospores [(6.6-) 7.4-8.2 (-8.9) 
<normalizedToken id="D707977BD6D3DAA0B35D872F4E3C84F9" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4.4-) 4.8-5.6 (-5.9) 
<normalizedToken id="9E6DEA35FD26F4CF086932C79BEB8222" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
or (6-) 7.5-9 (-10.5) 
<normalizedToken id="0503F41FDEF2457D41C128F6C83CE7D1" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4-) 4.5-5.5 (-6) 
<normalizedToken id="449E37B7DAE20DB3FCF62D45D663B83F" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
] and wider pileipellis hyphae (3-14.5 
<normalizedToken id="ED296F99B7699906207F7FB7AE866D3A" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
diam. or 9-14 
<normalizedToken id="A4BCCFF17C09CA6A63FC14FBDE3E9BAF" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
diam.) (
<bibRefCitation id="F00D9CD51751EF2C76692ED113FEC015" author="Petersen, RH" journalOrPublisher="Economic Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" refId="B45" refString="Petersen, RH, Ryvarden, L, 1971. Notes on cantharelloid fungi IV. Two new species of Cantharellus. Svensk Bot. Tidskr.65: 399-405." title="Notes on cantharelloid fungi IV. Two new species of Cantharellus. Svensk Bot. Tidskr. 65: 399 - 405." year="1971">Petersen and Ryvarden 1971</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A755FF644EC75B4FC32469B601E52FFC" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1978.12020280" author="Bigelow, HE" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="707 - 756" refId="B5" refString="Bigelow, HE, 1978. The cantharelloid fungi of New England and adjacent areas. Mycologia 70 (4): 707 - 756, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1978.12020280" title="The cantharelloid fungi of New England and adjacent areas." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1978.12020280" volume="70" year="1978">Bigelow 1978</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DEADAD850D3F4C1D2DCFF64FBB9CB58F" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
<taxonomicName id="E655992340AD0594FFF71F03007516CB" authorityName="M. Herrera, Bandala &amp; Montoya" authorityYear="2021" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Cantharellaceae" genus="Cantharellus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cantharellus parvoflavus" order="Cantharellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="parvoflavus">
<emphasis id="363177C35054AE8E96E63084BCD55499" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Cantharellus parvoflavus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to yellow forms of 
<taxonomicName id="186C42F044C4851787839C18C972C4C0" genus="C." lsidName="C. minor" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis id="F69D72B7442BB3FA087C87444FBC052E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. minor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, because they have a hygrophoroid appearance, but this latter is usually bright yellow orange to orange, fading to pale orange-buff or pale orange, with glabrous pileus surface, bigger, ellipsoid, slightly phaseoliform basidiospores (6-) 7.5-10 (-11.5) 
<normalizedToken id="6FE63FA635C4D47C2568BF2E2E167D61" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4-) 4.5-6 (-6.5) 
<normalizedToken id="FE32222597945295855B5393F81742E9" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
and pileipellis terminal elements subcylindrical to subventricose (
<bibRefCitation id="3269C58FFBD2F029FE36E15E4A223D47" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1978.12020280" author="Bigelow, HE" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="707 - 756" refId="B5" refString="Bigelow, HE, 1978. The cantharelloid fungi of New England and adjacent areas. Mycologia 70 (4): 707 - 756, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1978.12020280" title="The cantharelloid fungi of New England and adjacent areas." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1978.12020280" volume="70" year="1978">Bigelow 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="20F7BB72FA4EB02905593967578882AD" author="Buyck, B" journalOrPublisher="Cryptogamie, Mycologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="17 - 33" refId="B8" refString="Buyck, B, Lewis, DP, Eyssartier, G, Hofstetter, V, 2010. Cantharellus quercophilus sp. nov. and its comparison to other small, yellow or brown American chanterelles. Cryptogamie, Mycologie 31 (1): 17 - 33" title="Cantharellus quercophilus sp. nov. and its comparison to other small, yellow or brown American chanterelles." volume="31" year="2010">Buyck et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="F6EC2EECCEB3EC2CF63B2FFC09743B50" authorityName="Eyssart. &amp; Buyck" authorityYear="1999" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Cantharellaceae" genus="Cantharellus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cantharellus romagnesianus" order="Cantharellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="romagnesianus">
<emphasis id="D98FCFA3F3902A65F3DDF7FD578BF526" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Cantharellus romagnesianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is close to 
<taxonomicName id="0F09ACBEA8FF457C04E1470A8FFC2C5F" genus="C." lsidName="C. parvoflavus" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="parvoflavus">
<emphasis id="B66147349253E8A5759F18C5E17C5DD0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. parvoflavus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but it develops grey-brown colors in the pileus, its hymenophore has forked veins, often spaced, larger basidiospores [(8-) 9-11.5 (-12.5) 
<normalizedToken id="351CCBE0EFF57B6226BE2F12F787873E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-6 (-6.5), Q = 1.71-2.28] and with different shape (
<bibRefCitation id="795284183C2BD71D2DBBC7B47F432213" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-016-0376-7" author="Olariaga, I" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="263 - 292" refId="B43" refString="Olariaga, I, Moreno, G, Manjon, JL, Salcedo, I, Hofstetter, V, Rodriguez, D, Buyck, B, 2017. Cantharellus (Cantharellales, Basidiomycota) revisited in Europe through a multigene phylogeny. Fungal Diversity 83 (1): 263 - 292, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-016-0376-7" title="Cantharellus (Cantharellales, Basidiomycota) revisited in Europe through a multigene phylogeny." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-016-0376-7" volume="83" year="2017">Olariaga et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
